<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-22T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-22T08:00:00-05:00" n="685" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d685">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">764.00/8–2250: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d685fn1">This telegram was relayed to Budapest
                                at 11:30 a. m. on August 22.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-22T16:00:00+03:00">August 22,
                                    1950—4 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>475. Insofar as we are aware last article by Varga appearing Moscow press
                            published <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi> May 10. He had been in virtual
                            oblivion since 1947,<note n="2" xml:id="d685fn2">For consideration of
                                the possible improvement in the position of the prominent
                                Hungarian-born Soviet economist Yevgeny (Eugene) Samoylovich Varga
                                during 1949, see <ref target="frus1949v05#pg_545">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1949, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, pp. 545</ref>–<ref target="frus1949v05#pg_680">680</ref>
                                <hi rend="italic">passim</hi>.</note> the first article bearing his
                            by-line since that date having appeared <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi>
                            March 19, 1950. If he has now become more or less permanent technician
                            Hungarian regime,<note n="3" xml:id="d685fn3">Varga had been assigned in
                                mid-1950 as economic adviser to the Hungarian Government, but he had
                                returned to Moscow in September, where his position became more
                                favorable.</note> he would not be first satellite Communist to have
                            returned, perhaps somewhat under shadow, to country of origin.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>